SIMPLE: endorse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Endorse
<hw>En*dorse"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Endorsed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Endorsing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Formerly
<ets>endosse</ets>, fr. F. <ets>endosser</ets> to put on the back, to
endorse; pref. <ets>en-</ets> (L. <ets>in</ets>) + <ets>dos</ets> back,
L. <ets>dorsum</ets>. See <er>Dorsal</er>, and cf.
<er>Indorse</er>.]</ety> <def>Same as <er>Indorse</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Both <xex>endorse</xex> and <xex>indorse</xex> are used
by good writers; but the tendency is to the more general use of
<xex>indorse</xex> and its derivatives <xex>indorsee</xex>,
<xex>indorser</xex>, and <xex>indorsement</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Endorse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Endorse
<hw>En*dorse"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Her.)</fld> <def>A subordinary,
resembling the pale, but of one fourth its width (according to some
writers, one eighth).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Endorsee</ent>⟦br⟧
